




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Transition Times: Distributions Arising from Time Heterogeneous Poisson Processes
AU  - Lenk, Peter J.
AU  - Rao, Ambar G.
Y1  - 1995/07/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.41.7.1117
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.41.7.1117
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1117
EP  - 1129
VL  - 41
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The units of a heterogeneous population are subjected to shocks. A unit fails, or more generally, undergoes a change of state after a sufficient number of shocks. The shocks for a particular unit are assumed to arrive according to a time heterogeneous Poisson process. The time to a change of state, the transition time, for the unit has a generalized Γ (gamma) distribution. We assume that the intensity of the Poisson process and the number of shocks until the change of state vary independently across the units according to a Γ and negative binomial distribution, respectively. The distribution of the transition time is shown to be the generalized F distribution, which includes a number of standard distributions as special cases. We illustrate these results with two empirical examples: modelling coupon redemptions and traffic accidents. In the latter case, the intensity function of the Poisson process includes time varying predictor variables.
AB  - The units of a heterogeneous population are subjected to shocks. A unit fails, or more generally, undergoes a change of state after a sufficient number of shocks. The shocks for a particular unit are assumed to arrive according to a time heterogeneous Poisson process. The time to a change of state, the transition time, for the unit has a generalized Γ (gamma) distribution. We assume that the intensity of the Poisson process and the number of shocks until the change of state vary independently across the units according to a Γ and negative binomial distribution, respectively. The distribution of the transition time is shown to be the generalized F distribution, which includes a number of standard distributions as special cases. We illustrate these results with two empirical examples: modelling coupon redemptions and traffic accidents. In the latter case, the intensity function of the Poisson process includes time varying predictor variables.
